{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8a251ff6-98b7-4f19-bdc3-6fe07dcb06dc","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\n# From your local machine:\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't available (trimmed/AOT image), use the [standalone download](https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace) instead.\n- For production-grade collection with lower overhead, consider **`dotnet-collect`** with EventPipe or **`perf`** if the container has `SYS_ADMIN` / `CAP_PERFMON`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dabc3c95-238a-4666-add0-86fd3d3a1e2d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for advice on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":378,"requestId":"7644:F41F2:D5EF4F:FA936D:69FE8D8B"},"id":"b0c8d9ba-603d-4518-b313-ffd1e861d7c9","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:27:48.815Z","parentId":"f9425664-b848-4a47-91e6-ad514b20ddd4"}
